    "name": "Monte Carlo global sensitivity analysis — COU2 hemolysis prediction",
    "description": "A variance-based global sensitivity analysis (Sobol indices, N=10 000 Monte Carlo samples) was conducted on the hemolysis index prediction across all five operating points. Input parameters varied included: blood viscosity (±10%), hemolysis model coefficient C (±25%), hemolysis model exponent α (±15%), mesh resolution scaling factor (±20%), and turbulent Schmidt number (0.5–1.0). First-order and total-order Sobol indices were computed. The hemolysis model coefficient C and exponent α together account for 74% of output variance; turbulent Schmidt number contributes 18%; blood viscosity and mesh resolution together contribute the remaining 8%. The dominant sensitivity to the power-law hemolysis sub-model coefficients informed targeted experimental calibration against the FDA pump dataset, reducing the 95th-percentile prediction interval for NIH from ±0.0038 to ±0.0011 g/100 L after coefficient refinement.",
